Hello,

Our team is having issues with the CBA battery analyzer. The software takes a long time to analyze the AmpHr graph, and when the graph finally starts showing the results of the test, it is usually in a straight line. We also used the settings that AndyMark has provided. We are not sure if the issue is with the settings provided or if the software is defective. Any recommendations and suggestions on ways to troubleshoot this issue would be appreciated.

Thank you, Red Watch, Team 2720

posts.name: Gabe
posts.cooked:
Do you have a screenshot of the resulting graph? How long did you run the test for?

In our experience with the CBA it can take upwards of 2 hours to complete a full discharge test on a ‚ÄúGood‚Äù battery. Ones that fail often complete in under an hour. The total Amp-Hours at the end of the discharge is the metric you‚Äôre looking for.

posts.name: Brett B Bonner
posts.cooked:
akanksha:

Here is a screenshot of a past test

It looks like you are running at a .020A (that‚Äôs 20mA) discharge rate.  That‚Äôs very small draw for our relatively large batteries, and it can run at that rate almost indefinitely.

The CBA does up to 150W discharge, or ~12.5A at 12V.  I am not familiar with the CBA software, but in terms of settings: for ‚Äònew battery‚Äô break-in tests we run at 7.5A discharge and 10.8V cutoff voltage on our tester.  A full battery runs about 2 hours at that rate.  I think if you adjust your rate you will have much better results.  Don‚Äôt set the cutoff voltage much below 10.8 as it‚Äôs possible to damage cells by over-discharging (there are many other threads discussing these parameters if you want to understand more).

posts.name: Gabe
posts.cooked: The test looks configured correctly - 6 cells, 18 Ah @ 7.5A - but the test is currently only drawing 0.02A for some reason.  At the bottom it says ‚ÄúNone Selected‚Äù which has me thinking perhaps the CBA has somehow become disconnected either from the PC or the battery, but didn‚Äôt halt the test. If you haven‚Äôt already, I would try cancelling the test, and then double-check all the connections and begin a new test on another battery.
